Find command will not work with the Person class that is modelled
after a patient.

A find command that is able to search a specific field of a Person
will allow the command to be more precise.

Let's,
* update the Find command to work with the new Person class
* include the functionality to search by the id and ward field.
Branch integratepatient
Add addNotes command

Tests should use FieldContainsKeywordPredicate instead of
NameContainsKeywordPredicate.

PersonBuilder is lacking the withId and withWard functions.

Let's make tests use this FieldContainsKeywordPredicate and
implement the withId and withWard functions in PersonBuilder.

commitResults.messageBody:
Create an Appointment class that will be associated with a patient.
It follows the dd-MM-yyyy-HH-mm date time format.

Having this Appointment class will allow us to add the functionality
of keeping track of a patients appointment.

commitResults.messageTitle: Abstract Date Time Format into its own util class
commitResults.messageBody:
Having the DATE_TIME_FORMATTER in its own DateUtil class allows for
greater reusability and centralized management.

Let's create a DateUtil class and a DATE_TIME_FORMATTER field in it.

Appointment class does not depend on Person class.

Having a bi-directional relationship will be beneficial when we
want to search via Appointments.

Let's include a person field in Appointment.

Appointment class does not have a toString method.

Having a toString method can help in the debugging process as we
are able to visualize what data we are getting back.

Let's add a toString method for Appointment class.
Shift the static import line to it's correct grouping for styling.

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Make id field unique
commitResults.messageBody:
Name is the only unique field.

In a healthcare setting, there might be patients of the same name.
To ensure that users can still add multiple patients with the same
name, id field should be unique instead of name.

Let's make id field unique instead of name.

Defensive programming for the find command is not robust enough.

Having better defensive programming measures can make the product
more user friendly as there will be less unexpected cases.

Let's,
* handle the case where a user inputs white spaces after their
field (e.g. "find i/       ")
* include logging for debugging purposes

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename method in ArgumentMultimap for readability
Styling: Rename method and general styling
Create a list that keeps track of appointments
commitResults.messageBody:
We are unable to show the schedule independent of the search results for
patients.

Having a separate list that handles the patients that have valid
appointments to display will allow for simultaneous usage of both lists.

Let's implement an ObservableList to keep track of changes made to the
appointment list, as well as a FilteredList that can handle any
filtering.

Add a Predicate to verify if a person's appointment should be
displayed given a particular date.

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Make Date predicate check within a range
commitResults.messageBody:
AppointmentContainsDatePredicate only checks if the given date is equal
to the start or end date.

This will result in errors as an appointment that lasts multiple days
will not be properly checked for.

Let's make the test method in AppointmentContainsDatePredicate consider
the range of dates between the start and end date of the appointment.

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Improve defensive programming measures
commitResults.messageBody:
The test methods in the Predicate classes do not check if person is
null.

requiring the person to be non null adds an additional layer of
check to be done, making our product less susceptible to bugs.
Bug fix: Improve defensive programming measures

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Make Appointment list sorted
commitResults.messageBody:
The primary functionality of the schedule feature is to show the
user's schedule for a particular day. Hence, it makes sense for
the appointment list to be sorted.

Doing so will improve user experience as the results will be sorted,
making it easier for them to track their activities.

Let's use a SortedList to wrap around the filteredList to achieve
this functionality.

commitResults.messageBody:
Diagnosis fields has additional restrictions that may not be
practical for users.

Altering the diagnosis field constraints can allow for greater
real world modelling.

Let's make diagnosis field,
* accept any characters
* must have at least 1 alphabetic character
* have a limit of 100 characters
Simplify schedule date command

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Alter Medication field constraints
commitResults.messageBody:
Medication field does not have a character limit.

This will introduce unexpected errors if users try to input a very
long input.

Let's enforce a 100 character limit of medication.

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Alter Id field constraints
commitResults.messageBody:
Id field follows a strict format.

This will make the application less general and could potentially
remove value from the application.

Let's change the constraints to mimic real world examples more
carefully.

commitResults.messageTitle: Bug fix: Increase character limit for id
commitResults.messageBody:
Id has a character limit of 20.

There exists id in the real world that are longer than that, i.e.
UUID.

Let's increase the character limit to accomodate these situations.

DateTimeParseException does not print out a very user friendly
error message.

It might be beneficial to introduce a more human-like error response
to improve user experience.

Let's change the error message returned during
DateTImeParseExceptions.
